			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2016</a> paper:</span><br><i>Coupled Software Transformations — Revisited</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2997364.2997366">10.1145/2997364.2997366</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagM">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> Coupled transformations are motivated by co-evolution and maintenance of multiple related software artifacts.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> It treats coupled transformations as transformation mechanisms for keeping artifacts consistent.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5g.html"><span class="tagL">T5G: Traceability</span></a><ul><li> The core problem is maintaining consistency/relationships across artifacts, closely tied to traceability concerns.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It addresses coordination across collections of heterogeneous artifacts that must evolve together.
</li></ul></li></ul>
